From: BCM6362 bringup <bringup@example.invalid>
Subject: [PATCH] b43: preserve silicon-default Prefetch/BurstLen bits in DMA64
 RXCTL programming

b43's dmacontroller_setup() builds the DMA64 RXCTL value from zero
and writes it fresh:

	value = (ring->frameoffset << B43_DMA64_RXFROFF_SHIFT);
	value |= B43_DMA64_RXENABLE;
	value |= (addrext << B43_DMA64_RXADDREXT_SHIFT)
	    & B43_DMA64_RXADDREXT_MASK;
	if (!parity)
		value |= B43_DMA64_RXPARITYDISABLE;
	b43_dma_write(ring, B43_DMA64_RXCTL, value);

That clobbers three register fields that the proprietary wl driver
treats as silicon configuration values:

  bits 18..20  PrefetchThreshold
  bits 21..23  PrefetchControl
  bits 24..25  BurstLen

Static audit of the proprietary wl blob's RX engine programming
(wlDSL-3580_EU.o_save, SHA-256
a68a032673840c17a5981b0d00f16920ce992bca35ecdfba407bd6d488f28221)
shows it does NOT write RXCTL from zero. Instead, in dma_attach
@0x13e3c..0x13ea8 it samples RXCTL once at attach time (while the
register is at the silicon reset value) and caches the three byte
fields in the dma_info struct:

  pi->181 = (RXCTL >> 18) & 0x7   /* PrefetchThreshold */
  pi->186 = (RXCTL >> 21) & 0x7   /* PrefetchControl   */
  pi->187 = (RXCTL >> 24) & 0x3   /* BurstLen          */

Then _dma_rxenable @0x10964 re-injects them on every RXCTL
programming alongside the new RxEnable / RxOffset / AddrExt bits.

These values are not constants - they are silicon reset defaults
that vary by chip and core revision. For the BCM6362 SoC the
defaults happen to be benign on the integrated 802.11 die. For
BCM4352 sitting on the BCM6362 PCIe RC the defaults select a
prefetch/burst combination that the BCM4352 silicon is designed for
when talking to a host RC; clobbering them to zero leaves the chip
emitting inbound descriptor fetches with no prefetch and minimum
burst, which on this RC pairing contributes to the descriptor-fetch
I_PC master-abort fault observed in dmesg.

This patch:
  1. Adds three register-field defines in dma.h
     (B43_DMA64_RXPREFTHRESH_*, B43_DMA64_RXPREFCTL_*,
     B43_DMA64_RXBURSTLEN_*) for the bit ranges above.
  2. In dmacontroller_setup()'s DMA64 RX path, reads RXCTL first
     and ORs the three preserved fields into the new value, mirror-
     ing _dma_rxenable. Reading once at setup is equivalent to the
     OEM's attach-time cache: dmacontroller_setup always runs after
     a fresh bcma core reset (probe path or controller_restart),
     so RXCTL still contains the silicon defaults at this point.

A symmetric audit and patch for DMA64 TXCTL (the OEM equivalent
lives in dma64_txinit @0x134b8) is a separate change once the TX
bit layout is confirmed from the disassembly - the TX register
may have these fields at the same shifts or at different ones.

Other RXCTL features the OEM handles conditionally that b43
currently does not - notably OverflowContinue (bit 10, gated by
pi->fifoenable & 0x2) - are out of scope here: they need the
fifoenable provenance traced first.

Tested on: D-Link DSL-3580L (BCM6362 SoC via bcma-host-soc, b43
phy0 and BCM4352 via BCM6362 PCIe RC, b43 phy1).

Signed-off-by: BCM6362 bringup <bringup@example.invalid>
---
--- a/drivers/net/wireless/broadcom/b43/dma.h
+++ b/drivers/net/wireless/broadcom/b43/dma.h
@@ -118,6 +118,12 @@
 #define		B43_DMA64_RXPARITYDISABLE		0x00000800
 #define		B43_DMA64_RXADDREXT_MASK		0x00030000
 #define		B43_DMA64_RXADDREXT_SHIFT		16
+#define		B43_DMA64_RXPREFTHRESH_MASK	0x001C0000
+#define		B43_DMA64_RXPREFTHRESH_SHIFT	18
+#define		B43_DMA64_RXPREFCTL_MASK		0x00E00000
+#define		B43_DMA64_RXPREFCTL_SHIFT	21
+#define		B43_DMA64_RXBURSTLEN_MASK	0x03000000
+#define		B43_DMA64_RXBURSTLEN_SHIFT	24
 #define B43_DMA64_RXINDEX				0x24
 #define B43_DMA64_RXRINGLO				0x28
 #define B43_DMA64_RXRINGHI				0x2C
--- a/drivers/net/wireless/broadcom/b43/dma.c
+++ b/drivers/net/wireless/broadcom/b43/dma.c
@@ -716,7 +716,28 @@
 			addrlo = b43_dma_address(&ring->dev->dma, ringbase, B43_DMA_ADDR_LOW);
 			addrhi = b43_dma_address(&ring->dev->dma, ringbase, B43_DMA_ADDR_HIGH);
 
-			value = (ring->frameoffset << B43_DMA64_RXFROFF_SHIFT);
+			/* Preserve PrefetchThreshold (bits 18..20),
+			 * PrefetchControl (bits 21..23) and BurstLen
+			 * (bits 24..25) silicon reset defaults. The
+			 * proprietary wl driver caches these in dma_attach
+			 * @0x13e3c..0x13ea8 of the DSL-3580L OEM blob
+			 * (SHA-256 a68a0326...) and re-injects them on
+			 * every RXCTL programming in _dma_rxenable
+			 * @0x10964. b43 used to clobber them to zero, so
+			 * the DMA engine ended up doing descriptor fetches
+			 * with no prefetch and minimum burst - on BCM4352
+			 * over the BCM6362 PCIe RC that interacts badly
+			 * with the inbound TLP sizing and contributes to
+			 * the descriptor-fetch I_PC fault. Reading once
+			 * here is equivalent to the OEM's attach-time
+			 * cache because dmacontroller_setup runs while the
+			 * register is still at reset defaults (the bcma
+			 * core has just been reset). */
+			value = b43_dma_read(ring, B43_DMA64_RXCTL) &
+				(B43_DMA64_RXPREFTHRESH_MASK |
+				 B43_DMA64_RXPREFCTL_MASK |
+				 B43_DMA64_RXBURSTLEN_MASK);
+			value |= (ring->frameoffset << B43_DMA64_RXFROFF_SHIFT);
 			value |= B43_DMA64_RXENABLE;
 			value |= (addrext << B43_DMA64_RXADDREXT_SHIFT)
 			    & B43_DMA64_RXADDREXT_MASK;
